Title: Data Science for Social Climate Change Modelling: Emerging Technologies Review
Abstract: Data science is revolutionizing climate change research, enabling the development of sophisticated models that incorporate vast amounts of data to predict and mitigate the impacts of climate change on society. Social climate change modelling encompasses the integration of social, economic, and environmental factors into climate models, providing a comprehensive understanding of the complex interactions between human activities and the climate system. By leveraging big data analytics, machine learning algorithms, and advanced visualization techniques, data scientists are developing cutting-edge models that simulate climate change scenarios, evaluate adaptation and mitigation strategies, and explore the impacts of climate change on vulnerable populations. These models empower policymakers, businesses, and communities to make informed decisions and implement effective measures to address the challenges of climate change.

Title: Scientific discovery in the age of artificial intelligence
Abstract:
Scientific discovery in the age of artificial intelligence (AI) is characterized by unprecedented advancements. AI algorithms can analyze vast datasets, identify patterns, and generate hypotheses, accelerating the pace of scientific inquiry.

Machine learning models can accelerate scientific simulations, optimize experiments, and automate data analysis, freeing scientists to focus on higher-level research. AI-powered virtual assistants provide real-time information and insights, enhancing collaboration and decision-making.

AI tools enable discovery of new materials, drug candidates, and subatomic particles. They decipher complex biological systems, unravel climate patterns, and explore astrophysical phenomena. AI algorithms analyze genomic data, leading to breakthroughs in personalized medicine.

Despite its transformative potential, ethical considerations arise. Ensuring data privacy, algorithmic fairness, and mitigating bias is crucial. The integration of AI and human ingenuity promises to revolutionize scientific discovery, pushing the boundaries of knowledge and driving progress in diverse fields.

Title: Conducting and Writing Quantitative and Qualitative Research
Abstract:
**Conducting and Writing Quantitative and Qualitative Research**

Quantitative and qualitative research are two distinct approaches to scientific inquiry that involve collecting and analyzing data.

**Quantitative research** focuses on numerical data and employs statistical methods to test hypotheses. It aims to generalize findings to a larger population and often involves surveys, experiments, and structured observations.

**Qualitative research**, on the other hand, explores complex phenomena through direct engagement with participants. It aims to provide in-depth understanding and relies on methods such as interviews, focus groups, and ethnographic observations.

Both approaches have strengths and limitations. Quantitative research provides empirical evidence and allows for statistical analysis, while qualitative research generates rich insights and contextual understanding. Researchers must carefully consider the research question and their available resources when choosing an approach.

Writing up research involves presenting the findings in a clear and concise manner. Both quantitative and qualitative research reports typically include sections on methods, results, discussion, and conclusions. The writing style and specific reporting requirements may vary depending on the discipline and journal guidelines.

Title: Three-dimensional CNN-inspired deep learning architecture for Yoga pose recognition in the real-world environment
Abstract: Yoga pose recognition in real-world environments poses challenges due to variations in body shape, clothing, and background clutter. To address these challenges, we propose a three-dimensional (3D) CNN-inspired deep learning architecture that leverages both spatial and temporal information. The architecture consists of a 3D convolutional neural network (CNN) backbone followed by a recurrent neural network (RNN) module. The 3D CNN extracts spatial features from multiple frames of a video sequence, while the RNN captures temporal dependencies between the frames. The architecture is trained end-to-end on a large dataset of yoga videos collected in real-world environments. Experimental results show that the proposed architecture outperforms state-of-the-art methods in yoga pose recognition accuracy and robustness to variations.

Title: Creating theory: Encouragement for using creativity and deduction in qualitative nursing research
Abstract: In qualitative nursing research, theory creation is a critical phase involving the development of novel theoretical frameworks to explain phenomena. Encouraging creativity and deduction enhances the rigor and validity of theory generation. Creativity fosters the development of innovative ideas and perspectives, while deduction allows researchers to derive logical conclusions from the data. By combining creativity and deduction, researchers can generate grounded theories that are responsive to the research context and contribute to the advancement of nursing knowledge. Creativity stimulates the exploration of multiple interpretations, allowing researchers to identify patterns, connections, and new insights. Meanwhile, deduction enables researchers to test hypotheses and refine theories through systematic reasoning and data analysis. This process ensures that the developed theory is supported by empirical evidence and provides a robust explanation of the phenomenon under investigation.

Title: A Practical Guide to Writing Quantitative and Qualitative Research Questions and Hypotheses in Scholarly Articles
Abstract: Writing effective research questions and hypotheses is essential for conducting rigorous and meaningful scholarly research. This guide provides a practical framework for developing well-formed research questions and hypotheses for both quantitative and qualitative research. It covers key concepts such as the types of research questions and hypotheses, the characteristics of strong questions and hypotheses, and the process of developing and refining them. This guide also includes examples and exercises to help researchers apply these principles to their own research projects. By following the steps outlined in this guide, researchers can increase the clarity, rigor, and validity of their research.

Title: The myth of induction in qualitative nursing research
Abstract:
The myth of induction in qualitative nursing research refers to the misconception that data collection and analysis in qualitative research follow a strictly linear and inductive process. This myth suggests that researchers begin with raw data and gradually build up to more abstract concepts and theories through a bottom-up approach.

However, qualitative research is a complex and iterative process that involves constant interplay between data collection, analysis, and interpretation. Researchers often move back and forth between these phases, refining their understanding of the data as new insights emerge.

Inductive reasoning plays a role in qualitative research, but it is not the only or dominant mode of reasoning. Researchers also engage in deductive reasoning, abduction, and other forms of logical inference to make sense of their data.

Recognizing the myth of induction allows researchers to embrace the dynamic and interpretive nature of qualitative research. It encourages researchers to be open to evolving understandings and to seek multiple perspectives and interpretations of the data.

Title: The qualitative content analysis process
Abstract:
Qualitative content analysis is a research method for analyzing and interpreting non-numerical data, such as text, images, or videos. It involves identifying patterns, themes, and categories within the data and then interpreting their meaning. The process typically includes:

1. **Data collection:** Gathering the non-numerical data from interviews, observations, or documents.
2. **Data preparation:** Cleaning and organizing the data for analysis.
3. **Coding:** Assigning codes (labels) to segments of data based on identified themes or concepts.
4. **Theme identification:** Grouping codes into broader themes or categories that represent the data's main ideas.
5. **Interpretation:** Drawing conclusions and insights based on the identified themes and patterns.

Qualitative content analysis is commonly used in social sciences, humanities, and health research to explore subjective experiences, uncover hidden meanings, and gain a deeper understanding of complex phenomena.

Title: Reversible data hiding in encrypted images with multi-prediction and adaptive huffman encoding
Abstract: Reversible data hiding in encrypted images (RDHEI) aims to embed secret data into an encrypted image while allowing the original image to be perfectly recovered after data extraction. Traditional RDHEI methods often suffer from low embedding capacity and visual quality degradation. To address these limitations, this research proposes a novel RDHEI scheme with multi-prediction and adaptive Huffman encoding. The proposed scheme utilizes multiple predictors to generate prediction errors, which are then compressed using adaptive Huffman encoding. This technique reduces the redundancy in the prediction errors and improves the embedding capacity. Furthermore, the use of a distortion-aware embedding strategy ensures that the visual quality of the stego-image remains high. Experimental results demonstrate that the proposed scheme significantly outperforms existing RDHEI methods in terms of embedding capacity, visual quality, and computational efficiency.

Title: CPEB2 inhibit cell proliferation through upregulating p21 mRNA stability in glioma
Abstract:
CPEB2 (cytoplasmic polyadenylation element-binding protein 2) is a key regulator of gene expression that plays a crucial role in cell proliferation and cancer progression. In glioma, a type of brain tumor,CPEB2 has been found to inhibit cell proliferation by upregulating the stability of p21 mRNA.

p21 is a cyclin-dependent kinase (CDK) inhibitor that plays a critical role in cell cycle regulation and tumor suppression. CPEB2 binds to the 3' untranslated region (UTR) of p21 mRNA and promotes its polyadenylation, a process that stabilizes the mRNA and increases its translation. By increasing p21 mRNA stability, CPEB2 leads to increased p21 protein levels, which inhibits CDK activity and blocks cell cycle progression.

The inhibition of cell proliferation by CPEB2 through p21 upregulation has therapeutic implications for glioma treatment. Targeting CPEB2 or its downstream pathway could provide a novel strategy to suppress glioma cell growth and progression.

Title: Quantitative gait analysis and prediction using artificial intelligence for patients with gait disorders
Abstract: Quantitative gait analysis using artificial intelligence (AI) offers a promising approach for evaluating and predicting gait disorders. AI algorithms can process vast amounts of gait data, objectively quantifying gait parameters and identifying subtle gait abnormalities. This enables early diagnosis, personalized treatment planning, and monitoring of treatment outcomes. By integrating AI with motion capture systems, clinicians can accurately assess spatiotemporal parameters, joint kinematics, and muscle activation patterns. Furthermore, AI-based models can predict future gait patterns, facilitating proactive interventions to prevent falls and improve mobility. This technology empowers clinicians with data-driven insights, leading to more precise diagnoses, tailored care, and improved outcomes for patients with gait disorders.

Title: Physics-informed neural network reconciles Australian displacements and tectonic stresses
Abstract: Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) combine machine learning with physical laws to improve predictions in complex systems. We use PINNs to reconcile surface displacements and tectonic stresses in Australia, which are often inconsistent due to uncertainties in Earth's structure and loading history. Our PINN-based approach uses GPS and Interferometric Synthetic Aperture Radar data to constrain a viscoelastic Earth model and estimate the 3-D stress field. The results show that the surface displacements and tectonic stresses are consistent within uncertainties, providing new insights into the dynamics of the Australian continent. PINNs offer a promising tool for reconciling diverse geophysical observations and advancing our understanding of Earth's processes.

Title: Antibiotic quality and use practices amongst dairy farmers and drug retailers in central Kenyan highlands
Abstract: Antibiotic misuse is a major threat to public health, contributing to the rise of antimicrobial resistance. In the central Kenyan highlands, dairy farmers and drug retailers play a significant role in antibiotic use practices. However, there is limited data on their knowledge, attitudes, and practices regarding antibiotic quality and use. This study aimed to assess the quality of antibiotics sold at retail outlets and evaluate the knowledge, attitudes, and antibiotic use practices among dairy farmers and drug retailers in the central Kenyan highlands. A cross-sectional study was conducted involving 50 dairy farms and 20 drug retail outlets. Antibiotic samples were collected from the retail outlets and tested for quality using standard microbiological methods. Dairy farmers and drug retailers were interviewed using semi-structured questionnaires to assess their knowledge, attitudes, and antibiotic use practices. The study found that 20% of the antibiotic samples collected from retail outlets failed quality testing. Dairy farmers had limited knowledge about antibiotic use and misuse, with 60% using antibiotics without veterinary prescription. Drug retailers also lacked adequate knowledge about antibiotic quality and use, with 40% selling antibiotics without a prescription. These findings highlight the need for interventions to improve antibiotic quality and use practices in the central Kenyan highlands.

Title: Modelling the upwelling radiance detected in a seawater column for oil-in-water emulsion tracking
Abstract: Modelling the upwelling radiance detected in a seawater column is crucial for tracking oil-in-water emulsions. These emulsions, often resulting from oil spills or industrial discharges, can have detrimental effects on marine ecosystems. Remote sensing techniques, such as multispectral or hyperspectral imaging, provide a non-invasive means to detect and quantify these emulsions. However, accurately interpreting the detected radiance signals requires understanding the complex interactions between light, the emulsion, and the seawater. Modelling the upwelling radiance helps account for these interactions, enabling the determination of emulsion properties such as droplet size, concentration, and optical properties. By incorporating physical principles and radiative transfer theory, these models simulate the radiative transport processes within the seawater column, providing a more accurate representation of the observed radiance signals. This knowledge is essential for developing effective algorithms for emulsion detection, quantification, and monitoring, ultimately aiding in spill response efforts and environmental protection.

Title: A continuation-dynamic constitution analysis approach based on digital stable marker tracing and study on simulation of ecological tidal water diversion
Abstract: The continuation-dynamic constitution analysis method based on digital stable marker tracing was developed to study the simulation of ecological tidal water diversion. This method uses stable isotopes as tracers to label water sources and track their transport and transformation processes in the ecosystem. Digital technology is used to collect and analyze the tracer data, and mathematical models are established to simulate the tracer dynamics. This approach allows for a comprehensive understanding of the ecological effects of tidal water diversion and provides a scientific basis for ecological restoration and management in coastal areas.

Title: Association between functional outcomes and psychological variables in persons with spinal cord injury
Abstract: Individuals with spinal cord injury (SCI) often experience a range of psychological challenges that can impact their functional outcomes. Studies have explored the associations between psychological variables and functional outcomes, including mobility, self-care, and participation in activities. Psychological factors such as depression, anxiety, self-efficacy, and coping strategies have been found to influence functional outcomes. For example, higher levels of depression and anxiety have been associated with poorer mobility and self-care abilities. Conversely, higher self-efficacy and adaptive coping strategies have been linked to improved functional outcomes. Understanding these associations can guide the development of targeted interventions aimed at improving both psychological well-being and functional outcomes in individuals with SCI.

Title: Growth and developmental outcomes of infants with hypoxic ischemic encephalopathy
Abstract: Hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy (HIE) arises in infants when the brain becomes starved of oxygen and blood flow. Severe cases can lead to cerebral palsy, developmental delay, seizures, and cognitive impairment. The severity of HIE and the infant's age at the time of the event are important factors in determining the potential for growth and developmental outcomes. Early intervention and therapy can help improve outcomes for infants with HIE.

Title: Comparative analysis of methods to reduce activation signature gene expression in PBMCs
Abstract:
The activation signature is a set of genes that are upregulated in response to immune activation. These genes are involved in a variety of immune functions, including cell proliferation, cytokine production, and antigen presentation. Reducing the expression of activation signature genes can therefore help to suppress immune responses.

Several methods have been developed to reduce activation signature gene expression in PBMCs. These methods include:

* **Glucocorticoids:** Glucocorticoids are a class of steroids that have potent anti-inflammatory effects. They can reduce the expression of activation signature genes by binding to the glucocorticoid receptor and inhibiting the transcription of these genes.
* **Calcineurin inhibitors:** Calcineurin inhibitors are a class of drugs that inhibit the calcineurin phosphatase. Calcineurin is a key enzyme in the activation of T cells, and inhibiting its activity can therefore reduce the expression of activation signature genes.
* **mTOR inhibitors:** mTOR inhibitors are a class of drugs that inhibit the mTOR kinase. mTOR is a key regulator of cell growth and proliferation, and inhibiting its activity can therefore reduce the expression of activation signature genes.
* **JAK inhibitors:** JAK inhibitors are a class of drugs that inhibit the JAK kinases. JAKs are involved in the signaling pathways of a variety of cytokines, and inhibiting their activity can therefore reduce the expression of activation signature genes.

The choice of which method to use to reduce activation signature gene expression in PBMCs will depend on the specific needs of the patient.

Title: On the interpretability of part-prototype based classifiers: a human centric analysis
Abstract: Machine learning algorithms often produce complex models that are difficult to understand for humans. This lack of interpretability can hinder the adoption of machine learning in various domains, especially when high-stakes decisions are involved. Part-prototype based classifiers are a type of machine learning algorithm that has been shown to be effective in a variety of tasks. However, the interpretability of these classifiers has not been well-studied. In this paper, we conduct a human-centric analysis of the interpretability of part-prototype based classifiers. We find that these classifiers are generally interpretable, but that the interpretability can vary depending on the task and the data. We also identify several factors that can affect the interpretability of part-prototype based classifiers. Our findings have implications for the design and use of part-prototype based classifiers in real-world applications.

Title: dTrmt10Aimpacts Hsp70 chaperone m6A levels and the stress response in theDrosophilabrain
Abstract: dTrmt10A is a methyltransferase enzyme that adds an m6A modification to RNA molecules. In the Drosophila brain, dTrmt10A has been found to regulate the levels of m6A modification on the Hsp70 chaperone RNA. Hsp70 is a protein that is involved in the stress response, and its expression is increased in response to stress. The m6A modification on Hsp70 RNA has been found to decrease its stability, which leads to decreased levels of Hsp70 protein. This decrease in Hsp70 protein levels can impair the stress response in the brain, making it more susceptible to damage.

Title: The experience of a tertiary referral center with laparoscopic pyelolithotomy for large renal stones during 18 years
Abstract:
Laparoscopic pyelolithotomy (LP) is a minimally invasive technique for removing large renal stones. We aimed to analyze the outcomes of LP for large renal stones at a tertiary referral center.

We retrospectively reviewed the records of 102 patients who underwent LP for renal stones 2 cm between 2003 and 2020. The mean age of the patients was 47.3 years, and the mean stone size was 3.2 cm. The overall stone-free rate (SFR) was 92.2%, with a mean operative time of 125.5 minutes and a mean estimated blood loss of 150 mL. The complication rate was 8.8%, including 2 cases of bleeding requiring transfusion and 1 case of postoperative urinary fistula. The mean follow-up was 38.4 months, and the SFR at the last follow-up was 90.2%.

LP is a safe and effective technique for removing large renal stones, with a high SFR and a low complication rate. The long-term SFR is comparable to that of other minimally invasive techniques.

Title: Utilizing a novel high-resolution malaria dataset for climate-informed predictions with a deep learning transformer model
Abstract:
Malaria remains a devastating disease, particularly in sub-Saharan Africa. Climate change is expected to exacerbate malaria transmission by altering mosquito habitats and human behavior. Predicting malaria risk under future climate scenarios is crucial for effective control.

We introduce a novel, high-resolution dataset of historical malaria cases and climate data across Africa. We leverage this dataset to train a deep learning transformer model, which outperforms existing models in predicting malaria risk. Our model captures complex spatiotemporal patterns and provides probabilistic predictions, enabling more nuanced decision-making.

By incorporating climate projections into our model, we generate climate-informed predictions of future malaria risk. This allows health authorities to proactively identify vulnerable areas and implement targeted interventions. Our work demonstrates the power of high-resolution data and deep learning for advancing malaria prediction and climate adaptation strategies.

Title: Nesting behavior is associated with body weight and grip strength loss in mice suffering from experimental arthritis
Abstract:
Nesting behavior is a complex and instinctive behavior in mice that involves the collection and arrangement of materials to create a comfortable and safe environment. It has been found that nesting behavior is associated with body weight and grip strength loss in mice suffering from experimental arthritis. This suggests that nesting behavior may be a useful indicator of disease severity and progression in arthritis.

Studies have shown that mice with experimental arthritis exhibit a decrease in nesting behavior compared to healthy mice. This decrease in nesting behavior is associated with a decrease in body weight and grip strength, which are common symptoms of arthritis. The decrease in nesting behavior may be due to the pain and inflammation associated with arthritis, which can make it difficult for mice to engage in this complex behavior.

Title: A unique neuropsychophysiological approach to objectify emotion (dys)regulation in healthy older adults during the COVID-19 pandemic
Abstract: The COVID-19 pandemic has had a profound impact on the mental health of older adults. Neuropsychophysiological approaches offer a unique way to objectively assess emotion (dys)regulation in this population. This approach involves measuring physiological responses (e.g., heart rate, skin conductance) and brain activity (e.g., EEG, fMRI) in response to emotional stimuli. By examining the relationship between these measures, researchers can identify patterns of physiological and brain activity that are associated with emotion (dys)regulation. This information can be used to develop targeted interventions to improve emotional well-being in older adults during the COVID-19 pandemic and beyond.

Title: Facile band gap tuning in graphenebrucite heterojunctions
Abstract:
Facile Band Gap Tuning in GrapheneBrucite Heterojunctions

The electronic properties of graphene can be tailored by interfacing with other materials, leading to the formation of heterojunctions with unique optoelectronic properties. In particular, the band gap of graphene can be modulated by controlling the charge transfer at the heterojunction interface. Here, we report the facile band gap tuning in graphenebrucite heterojunctions via a simple wet-chemical synthesis method. The band gap of graphene can be continuously tuned from 0.2 to 0.8 eV by varying the brucite concentration in the heterojunction. The heterojunctions exhibit efficient photoluminescence with tunable emission wavelength, making them promising candidates for optoelectronic applications. Our findings provide a new strategy for band gap engineering in graphene-based heterostructures and pave the way for the development of novel optoelectronic devices.

Title: The molecular subtypes and clinical prognosis characteristic of tertiary lymphoid structures-related gene of cutaneous melanoma
Abstract:
Tertiary lymphoid structures (TLSs) are ectopic lymphoid aggregates that form in non-lymphoid tissues in response to chronic inflammation or infection. TLSs have been identified in a variety of human cancers, including cutaneous melanoma. The presence of TLSs in melanoma is associated with improved clinical prognosis.

Several studies have identified molecular subtypes of TLSs in cutaneous melanoma. These subtypes are characterized by distinct gene expression profiles and immune cell compositions. The most common TLS subtype is the follicular TLS, which is characterized by the presence of germinal centers and a high density of B cells and T cells. Other TLS subtypes include the interfollicular TLS, which is characterized by a diffuse distribution of immune cells, and the marginal zone TLS, which is characterized by the presence of a marginal zone of B cells.

The molecular subtypes of TLSs in cutaneous melanoma are associated with different clinical prognoses. Follicular TLSs are associated with the best prognosis, while interfollicular TLSs are associated with a worse prognosis. The presence of TLSs in melanoma is also associated with increased expression of immune checkpoint molecules, such as PD-1 and CTLA-4. These molecules can inhibit the anti-tumor immune response, and their expression is associated with worse clinical outcomes.

Title: A validated LCMS/MS method for simultaneous determination of key glucocorticoids in animal hair for applications in conservation biology
Abstract: A validated liquid chromatographytandem mass spectrometry (LCMS/MS) method was developed and validated for the simultaneous determination of six key glucocorticoids (GCs; cortisol, cortisone, corticosterone, 11-dehydrocorticosterone, prednisone, and prednisolone) in animal hair. The method involved a simple and rapid hair extraction procedure followed by LCMS/MS analysis. The method was validated in terms of linearity, accuracy, precision, recovery, matrix effects, and stability. The method was successfully applied to the analysis of hair samples from wild and captive animals, including African elephants, black rhinoceroses, and lions. The results demonstrated the potential of this method for non-invasive monitoring of GC levels in animals for applications in conservation biology, where assessing stress levels and reproductive status is crucial for species management and conservation.

Title: RTKN2 knockdown alleviates the malignancy of breast cancer cells by regulating the Wnt/-catenin pathway
Abstract: RTKN2 knockdown alleviates the malignancy of breast cancer cells by regulating the Wnt/-catenin pathway. RTKN2, a receptor tyrosine kinase-like orphan receptor 2, is highly expressed in breast cancer and associated with poor prognosis. Studies have shown that RTKN2 knockdown suppresses breast cancer cell proliferation, migration, invasion, and tumor growth in vivo. Mechanistically, RTKN2 knockdown inhibits the Wnt/-catenin pathway by reducing the expression of Wnt target genes, such as c-Myc and cyclin D1. This inhibition leads to decreased -catenin nuclear translocation and transcriptional activity, resulting in reduced cell proliferation and tumorigenesis. Therefore, RTKN2 knockdown alleviates the malignancy of breast cancer cells by regulating the Wnt/-catenin pathway, suggesting that RTKN2 could be a potential therapeutic target for breast cancer treatment.

Title: Use of Ranibizumab for evaluating focal laser combination therapy for refractory diabetic macular edema patients: an exploratory study on the RELAND trials
Abstract: The RELAND trials evaluated the efficacy and safety of combining focal laser therapy with intravitreal ranibizumab injections in refractory diabetic macular edema (DME) patients. Patients received either focal laser therapy alone or focal laser therapy plus ranibizumab. The primary endpoint was the change in best-corrected visual acuity (BCVA) at week 24. The results showed that the combination therapy group achieved significantly greater improvements in BCVA compared to the focal laser alone group. The combination therapy group also had a lower rate of disease progression and a higher rate of anatomic improvement. The study concluded that the combination of focal laser therapy and ranibizumab injections is an effective and safe treatment for refractory DME patients.

Title: Youngs double-slit experiment with undulator vortex radiation in the photon-counting regime
Abstract:
Young's double-slit experiment is a demonstration that light and matter can display characteristics of both classically defined waves and particles. In the photon-counting regime, where individual photons are detected, the experiment shows that each photon goes through both slits simultaneously, creating an interference pattern even when the photons are sent through the slits one at a time.

In this variation of the experiment, undulator vortex radiation is used as the light source. Undulator vortex radiation is a type of electromagnetic radiation that has a helical phase front. This results in a vortex beam, which has a central dark spot surrounded by a series of bright rings.

When undulator vortex radiation is used in Young's double-slit experiment, the interference pattern is modified. The central dark spot is replaced by a bright spot, and the bright rings are replaced by a series of dark rings. This modified interference pattern is due to the helical phase front of the undulator vortex radiation.

Title: Testing the effects of photobiomodulation on angiogenesis in a newly established CAM burn wound model
Abstract: Photobiomodulation (PBM) has been shown to have therapeutic effects in various wound healing models. However, its effects on angiogenesis in burn wounds remain unclear. This study aimed to investigate the effects of PBM on angiogenesis in a newly established chorioallantoic membrane (CAM) burn wound model. CAMs were harvested from 10-day-old fertilized chicken eggs and subjected to a standardized burn injury. The CAMs were then treated with PBM ( = 808 nm, 50 mW/cm2, 5 min) or sham treatment daily for 7 days. Angiogenesis was assessed by measuring the number of blood vessels and the expression of vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) mRNA and protein. The results showed that PBM significantly increased the number of blood vessels and the expression of VEGF mRNA and protein in CAM burn wounds. These findings suggest that PBM may promote angiogenesis in burn wounds and could be a potential therapeutic approach for burn wound healing.

Title: Pseudorabies virus causes splenic injury via inducing oxidative stress and apoptosis related factors in mice
Abstract:
Pseudorabies virus (PRV) is a neurotropic virus that affects swine. In addition to neurological symptoms, PRV infection can also cause splenic injury. The mechanisms underlying PRV-induced splenic injury are not fully understood, but oxidative stress and apoptosis are thought to play a role.

Oxidative stress occurs when there is an imbalance between the production of reactive oxygen species (ROS) and the ability of the body to detoxify ROS. Excessive ROS can damage cells and tissues, and it has been shown to contribute to the pathogenesis of PRV infection.

Apoptosis is a form of programmed cell death that is characterized by a series of biochemical events, including the activation of caspases. Caspases are enzymes that cleave proteins and lead to the dismantling of the cell. Apoptosis is essential for the maintenance of tissue homeostasis, but excessive apoptosis can lead to tissue damage.

Recent studies have shown that PRV infection induces oxidative stress and apoptosis in the spleen of mice. The induction of oxidative stress and apoptosis is mediated by the activation of the mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) pathway. The MAPK pathway is a signaling pathway that is involved in the regulation of cell growth, differentiation, and apoptosis.

Title: Association of altered fibrinogen indexes levels as a potential biomarker in determining the possible onset of diabetic retinopathy
Abstract:
**Association of Altered Fibrinogen Indexes Levels as a Potential Biomarker for Diabetic Retinopathy**

Diabetic retinopathy, a leading cause of blindness, often presents with no early symptoms. Fibrinogen, a protein involved in blood clotting, has been implicated in the development of diabetic complications. Alterations in fibrinogen indexes, such as fibrinogen concentration, fibrin clot turbidity, and plasma viscosity, have been observed in diabetic patients, especially those with retinopathy.

Studies suggest that elevated fibrinogen levels and increased clot turbidity may be associated with an increased risk of diabetic retinopathy. These alterations may contribute to impaired blood flow in the retinal microcirculation, leading to inflammation, oxidative stress, and microangiopathy.

Further research is needed to establish fibrinogen indexes as reliable biomarkers for predicting diabetic retinopathy onset. However, their potential role in disease monitoring and early intervention strategies, particularly in high-risk diabetic populations, warrants further investigation.

Title: Effect of surface morphology on optical properties of two multilayer structures CuO/ZnO/SiC and Al2O3/ZnO/SiC
Abstract: The optical properties of CuO/ZnO/SiC and Al2O3/ZnO/SiC multilayer structures are significantly influenced by their surface morphology. The surface morphology of these structures can be tailored by controlling the deposition conditions, such as temperature, pressure, and deposition rate. The surface morphology of the multilayer structures affects the optical properties, such as transmittance, reflectance, and absorption. For example, a multilayer structure with a rough surface morphology has a higher transmittance and a lower reflectance than a multilayer structure with a smooth surface morphology. This is because the rough surface morphology scatters the light, which reduces the reflectance and increases the transmittance.

Title: The relationship between nest location selection of Barn swallows (Hirundo rustica) and human activity and residence
Abstract: Barn swallows (Hirundo rustica) are aerial insectivores that often nest in close proximity to human habitation. The selection of nest sites by barn swallows is influenced by various factors, including human activity and residence. Studies have shown that barn swallows prefer to nest in areas with high levels of human activity, such as farms, barns, and stables, where they can easily access food and nesting materials. The presence of humans also provides protection from predators. However, the close proximity to human activity can also pose challenges for barn swallows, such as nest disturbance, noise pollution, and chemical exposure. Therefore, the relationship between nest location selection of barn swallows and human activity and residence is complex and influenced by both positive and negative factors.

Title: Increased sodium fluorescein transport by corticosteroids is inhibited by a LAT-1 specific inhibitor in retinal pigment epithelial cells in vitro
Abstract: Increased sodium fluorescein transport by corticosteroids is inhibited by a LAT-1 specific inhibitor in retinal pigment epithelial cells in vitro. This study investigated the effects of corticosteroids on sodium fluorescein (NaFl) transport in retinal pigment epithelial (RPE) cells and the involvement of the large neutral amino acid transporter 1 (LAT-1) in this process. Dexamethasone and hydrocortisone increased NaFl transport in a dose-dependent manner. The LAT-1 specific inhibitor JPH203 inhibited the corticosteroid-induced increase in NaFl transport. These results suggest that corticosteroids increase NaFl transport in RPE cells via the LAT-1 transporter, and that LAT-1 inhibition may be a potential therapeutic strategy for conditions associated with increased NaFl transport in the retina.

Title: Optogenetic induction of caspase-8 mediated apoptosis by employingArabidopsiscryptochrome 2
Abstract:
Optogenetic induction of caspase-8 mediated apoptosis by employing Arabidopsis cryptochrome 2

Apoptosis is a form of programmed cell death that is essential for the development and homeostasis of multicellular organisms. Caspase-8 is a key initiator caspase that activates the apoptotic cascade. Here, we report the development of an optogenetic system that allows for the specific induction of caspase-8 mediated apoptosis in mammalian cells. This system is based on the Arabidopsis cryptochrome 2 (CRY2) protein, which undergoes a conformational change upon blue light irradiation. We fused CRY2 to the N-terminus of caspase-8, and showed that this fusion protein (CRY2-caspase-8) is inactive in the dark, but undergoes a conformational change upon blue light irradiation, which allows it to dimerize and activate caspase-8. We then tested the ability of CRY2-caspase-8 to induce apoptosis in mammalian cells. We found that CRY2-caspase-8 can induce apoptosis in a dose-dependent manner, and that this apoptosis is dependent on caspase-8 activity. Furthermore, we showed that CRY2-caspase-8 can be used to induce apoptosis in a spatial and temporal manner using blue light illumination. This system provides a powerful new tool for studying apoptosis and for developing new therapeutic strategies for diseases that are characterized by dysregulated apoptosis.

Title: Estimation of heat transfer coefficient and friction factor with showering of aluminum nitride and alumina water based hybrid nanofluid in a tube with twisted tape insert
Abstract: Hybrid nanofluids are a new class of fluids that exhibit enhanced thermal properties compared to conventional fluids. In this study, the heat transfer coefficient and friction factor of an aluminum nitride and alumina water-based hybrid nanofluid flowing through a tube with a twisted tape insert were investigated. The results showed that the heat transfer coefficient and friction factor increased with increasing Reynolds number and volume fraction of the hybrid nanofluid. The twisted tape insert also enhanced the heat transfer and friction characteristics of the hybrid nanofluid. The experimental data were compared with the predictions of existing correlations, and the results showed good agreement.

Title: New insight in massive cerebral infarction predictions after anterior circulation occlusion
Abstract: Recent advances in multimodal neuroimaging have provided new insights into predicting the development of massive cerebral infarction (MCI) after anterior circulation occlusion (ACO). Perfusion imaging techniques, such as CT perfusion (CTP) and MR perfusion (MRP), can identify patients at high risk by assessing cerebral blood flow (CBF) and cerebral blood volume (CBV) in the ischemic penumbra. Advanced imaging methods, including diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI) and diffusion tensor imaging (DTI), can detect early signs of neuronal injury and white matter damage, respectively. Machine learning algorithms have demonstrated promising results in combining multiple imaging modalities to improve the prediction of MCI. Additionally, advanced physiological monitoring, such as continuous electroencephalography (cEEG) and intracranial pressure (ICP) monitoring, can provide real-time information on brain function and hemodynamics, further refining risk stratification. These novel approaches have significantly improved our ability to identify patients who may benefit from tailored neuroprotective interventions aimed at preventing MCI after ACO.

Title: A decision-making model for prediction of a stable disease course in chronic hepatitis B patients
Abstract:
**Decision-Making Model for Stable Disease Course Prediction in Chronic Hepatitis B Patients**

Chronic hepatitis B (CHB) is a prevalent liver disease that often requires long-term treatment. Predicting disease stability is crucial for guiding clinical management. This model provides a structured approach to assess factors associated with stable disease progression and predict the likelihood of a stable course.

The model incorporates clinical, laboratory, and virological parameters, including liver function tests, viral load, and host factors. Using statistical methods, it generates a score that estimates the probability of maintaining a stable disease course without significant flares or disease progression. The model aims to help clinicians identify patients who have a high likelihood of stable disease, allowing for tailored treatment plans and improved patient outcomes.

Title: Trajectory modeling of cannabis use over 30 years identifies five unique longitudinal patterns
Abstract:
This study looked at the cannabis use trajectories of over 30,000 people over a 30-year period. Five distinct patterns were identified:

1. **Early-onset persistent use:** This group started using cannabis early in their teens and continued to use it heavily throughout their lives.
2. **Early-onset desisting use:** This group also started using cannabis early in their teens, but they stopped using it by their early 20s.
3. **Late-onset escalating use:** This group started using cannabis in their late teens or early 20s, and their use gradually increased over time.
4. **Late-onset desisting use:** This group also started using cannabis in their late teens or early 20s, but they stopped using it within a few years.
5. **Non-use:** This group never used cannabis.

These findings suggest that there is no one-size-fits-all approach to cannabis use prevention and treatment. Interventions need to be tailored to the individual's specific risk factors and trajectory of use.

Title: Investigation of the effect of carnitine on cerebral vasospasm in experimental subarachnoid hemorrhage model
Abstract:
Subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH) is a devastating cerebrovascular disease characterized by bleeding into the subarachnoid space, the area surrounding the brain. Cerebral vasospasm, a major complication of SAH, is a narrowing of the cerebral arteries that can lead to ischemia and potentially devastating neurological deficits. Carnitine, a natural substance involved in energy metabolism, has been shown to have vasodilatory effects in other vascular beds.

In this study, the investigators sought to investigate the effect of carnitine on cerebral vasospasm in an experimental SAH model. Rabbits underwent SAH induction by injecting autologous blood into the cisterna magna. The rabbits were then randomized to receive either carnitine or saline intraperitoneally for 7 days after SAH. Cerebral vasospasm was assessed by measuring the diameter of the basilar artery using digital subtraction angiography at 3 and 7 days after SAH.

The results showed that carnitine treatment significantly reduced cerebral vasospasm compared to saline treatment. The basilar artery diameter was larger in the carnitine-treated group than in the saline-treated group at both 3 and 7 days after SAH. These findings suggest that carnitine may be a potential therapeutic agent for cerebral vasospasm after SAH.

Title: A novel double-sheath negative-pressure versus conventional minimally invasive percutaneous nephrolithotomy for large kidney stone
Abstract: A novel double-sheath negative-pressure (DSNP) percutaneous nephrolithotomy (PCNL), compared with conventional minimally invasive PCNL (MIP), was developed to improve the surgical efficacy and reduce complications in patients with large kidney stones. The DSNP technique employs two sheaths, with the inner sheath creating a negative pressure environment around the stone, facilitating stone fragmentation and aspiration. Studies have demonstrated that DSNP-PCNL offers several advantages over MIP-PCNL, including shorter operation time, higher stone-free rates, and reduced blood loss, without compromising safety. The DSNP technique has emerged as a promising alternative for managing large kidney stones, providing improved clinical outcomes and potentially reducing the risk of complications.

Title: Assessing the cyclic fatigue resistance and sterilization effects on replica-like endodontic instruments compared to Reciproc Blue
Abstract: Cyclic fatigue resistance and sterilization effects were evaluated for replica-like endodontic instruments (RLEIs) compared to Reciproc Blue (RB). RLEIs were manufactured using NiTi ingots with the same composition as RB. Instruments were subjected to cyclic fatigue testing in a simulated root canal model. The number of cycles to failure (NCF) was recorded. Sterilization effects were evaluated by exposing instruments to autoclaving, dry heat, or ethylene oxide (EO) sterilization methods. The NCF of RLEIs was significantly lower than that of RB in the autoclaving and dry heat groups. However, there was no significant difference in NCF between RLEIs and RB in the EO group. All sterilization methods significantly reduced the NCF of both RLEIs and RB. These results suggest that RLEIs have similar cyclic fatigue resistance and sterilization effects compared to RB, except for reduced NCF after autoclaving and dry heat sterilization.

Title: Effect of renin angiotensin system inhibitors on long-term major cardiovascular outcomes in patients with high atherosclerotic cardiovascular risk
Abstract:
Renin angiotensin system inhibitors (RASIs) are commonly used to manage hypertension and heart failure. Studies have examined their long-term effects on major cardiovascular outcomes in patients with high atherosclerotic cardiovascular risk. 

Evidence suggests that RASIs, particularly angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors and angiotensin II receptor blockers (ARBs), may reduce the risk of major adverse cardiovascular events (MACE), including myocardial infarction, stroke, and cardiovascular death, in these patients. They have been shown to lower blood pressure and improve left ventricular function, which can lead to a reduction in cardiovascular morbidity and mortality. 

However, the specific benefits and risks of RASIs in this population may vary depending on individual patient characteristics and the type of RASI used. Further research is needed to determine the optimal use of RASIs in patients with high atherosclerotic cardiovascular risk.

Title: Success and safety of deep sedation as a primary anaesthetic approach for transvenous lead extraction: a retrospective analysis
Abstract: Deep sedation as a primary anesthetic approach for transvenous lead extraction offers several advantages, including reduced risks of complications, shorter recovery times, and cost-effectiveness. This retrospective analysis of 100 patients undergoing transvenous lead extraction under deep sedation found a high success rate (98%) and a low complication rate (2%). The study highlights the safety and efficacy of deep sedation as a primary anesthetic approach for this procedure and suggests that it is a viable alternative to general anesthesia.

Title: 3D-printed low-cost choke corrugated Gaussian profile horn antenna for Ka-band
Abstract: A low-cost 3D-printed choke corrugated Gaussian profile horn antenna is a type of antenna that is used to transmit and receive electromagnetic radiation in the Ka-band (26.5-40 GHz). It is fabricated using 3D printing technology, which allows for rapid and cost-effective production. The antenna is designed with a choke corrugated surface, which helps to reduce side lobes and improve the directivity of the antenna. The Gaussian profile of the antenna provides a focused beam with low side lobes, making it suitable for applications such as satellite communications and radar systems. The low cost and ease of fabrication make it an attractive option for various applications requiring high-performance antennas in the Ka-band.

Title: Citrullinated and MMP-degraded vimentin is associated with chronic pulmonary diseases and genetic variants in PADI3/PADI4 and CFH in postmenopausal women
Abstract: Citrullinated and matrix metallopeptidase (MMP)-degraded vimentin are elevated in the airways of patients with chronic pulmonary diseases. Genetic variants in peptidylarginine deiminase 3/4 (PADI3/PADI4) and complement factor H (CFH) are associated with increased levels of these vimentin isoforms in postmenopausal women. Citrullination and MMP-degradation of vimentin may contribute to the pathogenesis of chronic pulmonary diseases by promoting inflammation, fibrosis, and airway remodeling. These findings suggest that targeting PADI3/PADI4 and CFH could be potential therapeutic strategies for chronic pulmonary diseases.

Title: Experimental study and simulations of hydrogen cooling effectiveness for aviation PEM fuel cells
Abstract: Experimental study and simulations of hydrogen cooling effectiveness for aviation PEM fuel cells are crucial for optimizing the performance and durability of hydrogen-powered aircraft. Experimental studies involve varying hydrogen flow rates and monitoring cell temperatures to determine the cooling effectiveness. Simulations using computational fluid dynamics (CFD) models allow for detailed analysis of hydrogen flow patterns and temperature distributions within the fuel cell stack. By combining experimental data and CFD simulations, researchers can optimize cooling strategies, such as hydrogen channel design and flow distribution, to enhance heat removal and improve fuel cell performance under aviation-specific conditions, such as high altitude and variable power demands. This research contributes to the development of efficient and reliable PEM fuel cells for aviation applications, enabling the transition to zero-emission flight.

Title: Prevalence and clinical relevance of liver dysfunction after thoracic surgery: a retrospective study
Abstract:
**Prevalence and Clinical Relevance of Liver Dysfunction after Thoracic Surgery: A Retrospective Study**

Liver dysfunction after thoracic surgery is a common complication that can impact patient outcomes. This retrospective study investigates the prevalence and clinical significance of liver dysfunction in a cohort of patients undergoing thoracic surgery.

A total of 100 patients undergoing major thoracic surgery were included. Liver function was assessed using serum alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and aspartate aminotransferase (AST) levels before and after surgery. Liver dysfunction was defined as an elevation of ALT or AST to >3 times the upper limit of normal.

The prevalence of liver dysfunction was 18% (n=18) within the first 3 days after surgery. Patients with liver dysfunction had significantly higher rates of postoperative complications (44% vs 12%, P<0.01) and longer hospital stays (12 vs 8 days, P<0.01). Additionally, liver dysfunction was associated with an increased risk of in-hospital mortality (11% vs 1%, P<0.05).

This study highlights the prevalence and clinical relevance of liver dysfunction after thoracic surgery. Early identification and management of liver dysfunction may improve patient outcomes and reduce the risk of postoperative complications.

Title: A signal recognition particle receptor gene from the sea cucumber,Apostichopus japonicas
Abstract:
The signal recognition particle (SRP) receptor is a protein complex that is responsible for the recognition and binding of the signal recognition particle (SRP). The SRP is a ribonucleoprotein complex that is involved in the targeting of proteins to the endoplasmic reticulum (ER). The SRP receptor is a membrane-bound protein complex that is located in the ER membrane. It consists of two subunits, alpha and beta. The alpha subunit is responsible for the binding of the SRP, while the beta subunit is responsible for the translocation of the protein into the ER.

A novel signal recognition particle receptor gene from the sea cucumber, Apostichopus japonicas, has been cloned and characterized. The gene encodes a protein of 446 amino acids with a calculated molecular mass of 49.2 kDa. The protein contains a signal peptide, a transmembrane domain, and a cytoplasmic domain. The cytoplasmic domain contains a conserved SRP-binding domain. The gene is expressed in a variety of tissues, including the intestine, muscle, and ovary. The expression of the gene is upregulated in response to stress. The gene is located on chromosome 11.

Title: Impact of anthropogenic accumulation on phytoplankton community and harmful algal bloom in temporarily open/closed estuary
Abstract: Increased human activities exacerbate nutrient enrichment and sediment inputs into coastal waters, leading to anthropogenic accumulation in temporarily open/closed estuaries (TOCEs). This accumulation alters environmental conditions and profoundly impacts the phytoplankton community. Phytoplankton diversity and biomass often decline, with dominance by small-sized and bloom-forming species. Nutrient imbalances and increased water residence time favor the growth of harmful algae, leading to harmful algal blooms (HABs). HABs can produce toxins that pose significant risks to human health, marine organisms, and coastal ecosystems. Understanding and mitigating the impact of anthropogenic accumulation on phytoplankton and HABs in TOCEs is crucial for the sustainable management of coastal waters and ecosystem health.

Title: A simple and rapid assay of lysosomal-targeting CDy6 for long-term real-time viability assessments in 2D and 3D in vitro culture models
Abstract: A simple and rapid assay of lysosomal-targeting CDy6 for long-term real-time viability assessments in 2D and 3D in vitro culture models. Long-term monitoring of cell viability is essential for studying cell proliferation, differentiation, and cytotoxicity. Conventional methods often require endpoint measurements, which can be time-consuming and labor-intensive. Here, we present a novel assay based on the lysosomal-targeting protein CDy6 for real-time, non-invasive viability monitoring in both 2D and 3D culture models. CDy6 is a lysosomal protein that exhibits increased expression in stressed or dying cells. We developed a CDy6-based biosensor, which consists of a CDy6-specific antibody conjugated to a fluorescent dye. The biosensor specifically binds to CDy6 on the lysosomal membrane, allowing for real-time visualization and quantification of lysosomal activity. Using this assay, we demonstrate that CDy6 expression can serve as a reliable indicator of cell viability, and that it can be used to monitor cell death over extended periods in both 2D and 3D culture models. This assay offers a simple, rapid, and non-invasive method for long-term cell viability assessments, making it a valuable tool for a wide range of applications in cell biology, drug discovery, and tissue engineering.

Title: Leveraging stylometry analysis to identify unique characteristics of peer support user groups in online mental health forums
Abstract: Stylometry analysis is a technique that can be used to identify unique characteristics of peer support user groups in online mental health forums. By analyzing the writing style of users, it is possible to determine their level of engagement, their emotional state, and their overall communication style. This information can then be used to tailor interventions and support services to the specific needs of each group. For example, users who are highly engaged in a forum may be more likely to benefit from peer support, while users who are expressing negative emotions may need more intensive support. Stylometry analysis can also be used to identify users who are at risk for suicide or self-harm, so that they can be provided with the appropriate help.

Title: Material aspects of sintering of EAC-1A lunar regolith simulant
Abstract:
Sintering is a crucial process in the preparation of lunar regolith simulants for use in scientific research and space exploration. EAC-1A is a well-known lunar regolith simulant developed by the European Space Agency (ESA). Understanding the material aspects of sintering EAC-1A is essential for optimizing the sintering process and controlling the properties of the sintered products.

During sintering, the particles in EAC-1A undergo various physical and chemical changes. The applied heat causes the particles to rearrange and bond together, forming a more cohesive and consolidated material. The sintering temperature, heating rate, and holding time all influence the final properties of the sintered product.

The material aspects of sintering EAC-1A include the particle size, shape, composition, and surface morphology of the starting material. These factors affect the sintering kinetics, the formation of interparticle bonds, and the development of microstructural features within the sintered product. The presence of volatile components, such as water or hydroxyl groups, can also influence the sintering process by promoting or inhibiting densification.

By studying the material aspects of sintering EAC-1A, researchers can gain insights into the fundamental mechanisms governing the sintering process and tailor the sintering parameters to achieve specific properties for the sintered products. This knowledge is valuable for the development of advanced lunar regolith simulants and the utilization of lunar regolith in future space missions.

Title: Enhanced performance of proton exchange membrane fuel cells by Pt/carbon/antimony-doped tin dioxide triple-junction catalyst
Abstract: Enhanced performance of proton exchange membrane fuel cells (PEMFCs) is achieved by employing a Pt/carbon/antimony-doped tin dioxide (Pt/C/Sb-SnO2) triple-junction catalyst. The incorporation of Sb-SnO2 into the catalyst structure effectively promotes the utilization of Pt, enhances the oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) activity, and improves the stability of the catalyst. The Pt/C/Sb-SnO2 catalyst exhibits superior ORR activity and durability compared to commercial Pt/C catalysts, resulting in significantly improved PEMFC performance. The increased power density and reduced degradation rate demonstrate the potential of the Pt/C/Sb-SnO2 triple-junction catalyst for practical PEMFC applications.

Title: Psychometric analysis of the body responsiveness questionnaire in the Portuguese population
Abstract: Psychometric analysis of the Body Responsiveness Questionnaire (BRQ) in the Portuguese population: The BRQ is a self-report measure of body responsiveness, which is the tendency to experience physical sensations in response to emotional states. The BRQ has been translated into Portuguese and validated in a sample of 105 Portuguese adults. The results of the psychometric analysis showed that the Portuguese version of the BRQ has good internal consistency, test-retest reliability, and construct validity. The BRQ was also found to be sensitive to changes in body responsiveness over time. These findings suggest that the Portuguese version of the BRQ is a valid and reliable measure of body responsiveness in the Portuguese population.

Title: A novel deep learning model for a computed tomography diagnosis of coronary plaque erosion
Abstract:
Coronary plaque erosion is an important cause of acute coronary syndrome, and its early and accurate diagnosis is crucial for guiding clinical decision-making. Computed tomography (CT) angiography is a non-invasive imaging technique that can be used to visualize coronary plaques. However, the diagnosis of plaque erosion based on CT images is challenging due to the limitations of conventional image analysis methods.

In this paper, we propose a novel deep learning model for the diagnosis of coronary plaque erosion based on CT images. The proposed model is based on a convolutional neural network (CNN) architecture, which has been shown to be effective for image classification tasks. The model was trained on a large dataset of CT images of coronary plaques, and its performance was evaluated on an independent test dataset. The proposed model achieved high accuracy in the diagnosis of plaque erosion, outperforming conventional image analysis methods.

The proposed model has the potential to improve the accuracy of CT-based diagnosis of coronary plaque erosion. This could lead to better patient care, as it would allow clinicians to more accurately identify patients at risk of acute coronary syndrome.

Title: Impact of crystalline orientation on CuCu solid-state bonding behavior by molecular dynamics simulations
Abstract: The impact of crystalline orientation on CuCu solid-state bonding behavior is investigated using molecular dynamics simulations. Four different grain boundary structures, 3(111), 5(210), 9(221), and 11(113), are considered. The results show that the bonding strength and bonding mechanism are significantly influenced by the crystalline orientation. The 3(111) grain boundary exhibits the highest bonding strength, while the 11(113) grain boundary exhibits the weakest bonding strength. The bonding mechanism is found to be a combination of atomic interdiffusion and plastic deformation. The atomic interdiffusion is more pronounced for the 3(111) grain boundary, while the plastic deformation is more pronounced for the 11(113) grain boundary. These findings provide insights into the role of crystalline orientation in solid-state bonding and can be used to guide the design of high-strength CuCu joints.

Title: Semaglutide reduces tumor burden in the GAN diet-induced obese and biopsy-confirmed mouse model of NASH-HCC with advanced fibrosis
Abstract: Semaglutide, a glucagon-like peptide-1 receptor agonist, has shown promise in treating nonalcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) and its associated liver fibrosis and hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). In this study, we investigated the effects of semaglutide on tumor burden in a biopsy-confirmed mouse model of NASH-HCC. NASH and HCC were induced in mice by a high-fat, high-cholesterol diet, followed by a choline-deficient, L-amino acid-defined diet. Mice were randomized to receive semaglutide or saline for 12 weeks. Semaglutide significantly reduced tumor burden by 63% compared to saline-treated mice (P < 0.05). This reduction was associated with decreased tumor cell proliferation and increased tumor cell apoptosis. Semaglutide also improved hepatic steatosis, inflammation, and fibrosis. These findings suggest that semaglutide may be a promising therapeutic option for NASH-HCC.

Title: Antithrombotic and prohemorrhagic actions of different concentrations of apixaban in patients exposed to single and dual antiplatelet regimens
Abstract: Apixaban, an oral direct factor Xa inhibitor, is widely used for anticoagulation in patients with atrial fibrillation, deep vein thrombosis, and pulmonary embolism. However, its antithrombotic and prohemorrhagic effects in patients receiving antiplatelet therapy are not fully understood. This study aimed to investigate the impact of different apixaban concentrations on thrombin generation and platelet function in patients exposed to single and dual antiplatelet regimens. Results showed that apixaban inhibited thrombin generation and platelet activation in a concentration-dependent manner, with a stronger effect observed in patients receiving dual antiplatelet therapy. These findings suggest that apixaban may have enhanced antithrombotic efficacy in patients on antiplatelet therapy, but the risk of bleeding should be carefully considered when determining the optimal apixaban concentration.

Title: Copper pyrithione and zinc pyrithione induce cytotoxicity and neurotoxicity in neuronal/astrocytic co-cultured cells via oxidative stress
Abstract:
Copper pyrithione (CuPT) and zinc pyrithione (ZnPT) are widely used biocides and antifungal agents. Concerns have been raised about their neurotoxic effects, but the underlying mechanisms remain elusive. This study aimed to investigate the cytotoxic and neurotoxic effects of CuPT and ZnPT in neuronal/astrocytic co-cultured cells and explore the role of oxidative stress.

Our results demonstrate that CuPT and ZnPT induce dose-dependent cytotoxicity and neurotoxicity in neuronal/astrocytic co-cultured cells. They cause significant decreases in cell viability and neurite outgrowth, as well as increases in lactate dehydrogenase release and intracellular reactive oxygen species (ROS) levels. Furthermore, CuPT and ZnPT treatment leads to mitochondrial dysfunction, as evidenced by decreased mitochondrial membrane potential and increased mitochondrial ROS production.

Inhibition of ROS generation or enhancement of antioxidant defense can partially alleviate CuPT- and ZnPT-induced cytotoxicity and neurotoxicity. These findings suggest that oxidative stress plays a crucial role in CuPT- and ZnPT-induced neurotoxicity. This study provides new insights into the neurotoxic mechanisms of CuPT and ZnPT, highlighting the need for further evaluation of their safety and potential health risks.

Title: White shark optimizer with optimal deep learning based effective unmanned aerial vehicles communication and scene classification
Abstract:
The White Shark Optimizer (WSO) is a bio-inspired optimization algorithm that mimics the hunting behavior of white sharks. It has been successfully applied to solve various optimization problems, including communication and scene classification tasks in unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs).

In this research, we propose a novel optimization framework based on WSO and deep learning for effective UAV communication and scene classification. The proposed framework consists of two main components:

1) WSO-based UAV Communication: We formulate the UAV communication problem as an optimization problem and solve it using WSO. The WSO algorithm is used to optimize the communication parameters, such as transmission power, modulation scheme, and coding rate, to maximize the communication performance while minimizing the energy consumption.

2) Deep Learning-based Scene Classification: We employ a deep convolutional neural network (DCNN) for scene classification. The DCNN is trained on a large dataset of images captured by UAVs. The trained DCNN can classify different scenes, such as urban, rural, forest, and water, with high accuracy.

The proposed framework has been evaluated on a real-world UAV platform. The results show that the WSO-based UAV communication algorithm can significantly improve the communication performance and reduce the energy consumption of UAVs. The deep learning-based scene classification algorithm can classify different scenes with high accuracy, which is essential for UAV navigation and mission planning.

Title: A novel approach using nonlinear surfaces for dynamic aperture optimization in MBA synchrotron light sources
Abstract: Dynamic aperture (DA) limitations in synchrotrons result from nonlinearities in the magnetic field. Here, a novel technique is presented to optimize the DA using nonlinear surfaces. The nonlinear field is expanded into a series of polynomials in the transverse coordinates, and the coefficients are optimized to minimize the DA. This approach is applied to the MAX IV storage ring, and a significant improvement in the DA is achieved. This technique provides a promising tool for optimizing the DA in existing and future synchrotron light sources.

Title: Novel sofosbuvir derivatives against SARS-CoV-2 RNA-dependent RNA polymerase: an in silico perspective
Abstract: Sofosbuvir, an FDA-approved antiviral drug, has demonstrated promising activity against SARS-CoV-2, the virus causing COVID-19. However, the emergence of resistant variants necessitates the development of novel sofosbuvir derivatives with enhanced potency and resistance profiles. This in silico study employed molecular docking, molecular dynamics simulations, and free energy calculations to identify novel sofosbuvir derivatives with improved inhibitory activity against SARS-CoV-2 RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (RdRp), a key enzyme in viral replication. The study revealed several derivatives with significantly higher binding affinity to RdRp compared to sofosbuvir, suggesting their potential as promising candidates for further optimization and experimental validation. These findings contribute to the ongoing efforts to develop effective antiviral therapies against SARS-CoV-2.

Title: A variable sampling plan based on the coefficient of variation for lots resubmission
Abstract:
A variable sampling plan based on the coefficient of variation (CV) for lot resubmission is a statistical method used in quality control to determine whether a lot of products meets a specified quality standard. The plan is based on the assumption that the CV of the lot is known. The CV is a measure of the variability of the lot, and it is defined as the ratio of the standard deviation of the lot to the mean of the lot.

The plan is implemented by taking a sample of products from the lot and measuring the quality of each product in the sample. The CV of the sample is then calculated, and it is compared to a predetermined acceptance criterion. If the CV of the sample is less than or equal to the acceptance criterion, then the lot is accepted. Otherwise, the lot is rejected and resubmitted for further inspection.

The CV-based variable sampling plan is a powerful tool for quality control, and it can be used to improve the quality of products by reducing the number of defective products that are shipped to customers.

Title: Unconjugated bilirubin is correlated with the severeness and neurodevelopmental outcomes in neonatal hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy
Abstract: Unconjugated bilirubin is a neurotoxin that can cause kernicterus, a potentially fatal condition that affects newborns. Kernicterus is characterized by bilirubin deposition in the brain, which can lead to permanent neurological damage. In neonatal hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy (HIE), a condition caused by oxygen deprivation to the brain during birth, unconjugated bilirubin levels are often elevated. Studies have shown that higher levels of unconjugated bilirubin in newborns with HIE are correlated with increased severity of the condition and poorer neurodevelopmental outcomes, including cerebral palsy, cognitive impairment, and hearing loss.

Title: Changes of the bacterial composition in duodenal fluid from patients with liver cirrhosis and molecular bacterascites
Abstract: Changes in the bacterial composition of duodenal fluid from patients with liver cirrhosis and molecular bacterascites have been observed. Patients with liver cirrhosis often have an altered gut microbiota, characterized by a decrease in beneficial bacteria and an increase in potentially harmful bacteria. This dysbiosis is associated with the development of complications such as hepatic encephalopathy and spontaneous bacterial peritonitis. Molecular bacterascites is a condition characterized by the presence of bacterial DNA in ascitic fluid, which is associated with a higher risk of infection and mortality. Studies have shown that patients with liver cirrhosis and molecular bacterascites have a distinct bacterial composition in their duodenal fluid compared to those without molecular bacterascites. These changes include an increase in the abundance of potentially pathogenic bacteria, such as Enterobacteriaceae and Pseudomonas, and a decrease in the abundance of beneficial bacteria, such as Lactobacilli and Bifidobacteria. These alterations in the bacterial composition may contribute to the development and progression of liver cirrhosis and its complications.

Title: Acute smartphone use impairs vigilance and inhibition capacities
Abstract: Acute smartphone use has been linked to impairments in vigilance and inhibition capacities. Studies have shown that individuals who use their smartphones excessively are more likely to experience lapses in attention and have difficulty controlling their impulsive behaviors. This is because smartphone use can interfere with the brain's ability to process information and make decisions. The constant stream of notifications and distractions from smartphones can overload the brain, making it more difficult to focus and concentrate. Additionally, the use of smartphones can lead to decreased levels of dopamine, a neurotransmitter that is involved in reward and motivation. This can make it more difficult to resist impulsive behaviors and maintain attention.

Title: Plant-expressed Zika virus envelope protein elicited protective immunity against the Zika virus in immunocompetent mice
Abstract:
The Zika virus is a mosquito-borne virus that has caused significant global health concerns. The virus can cause a range of symptoms, including fever, rash, headache, and joint pain, and can also lead to more severe complications such as Guillain-Barr syndrome and microcephaly in infants. Currently, there is no approved vaccine or treatment for Zika virus infection.

One promising approach to developing a Zika virus vaccine is to use plant-expressed proteins. Plant-produced proteins are safe and cost-effective, and they can be easily scaled up for large-scale production. A recent study found that plant-expressed Zika virus envelope protein was able to elicit protective immunity against the virus in immunocompetent mice. The mice that were vaccinated with the plant-expressed protein were protected from Zika virus infection, and they did not develop any symptoms of disease. These findings suggest that plant-expressed Zika virus envelope protein could be a promising candidate for a Zika virus vaccine.

Title: Exploring the infiltrative and degradative ability ofFusarium oxysporumon polyethylene terephthalate (PET) using correlative microscopy and deep learning
Abstract: Fusarium oxysporum is a fungus that has been shown to degrade polyethylene terephthalate (PET), a synthetic polymer commonly used in plastic bottles and other packaging materials. This study used correlative microscopy and deep learning to investigate the infiltrative and degradative ability of F. oxysporum on PET. Correlative microscopy allowed for the visualization of the fungus in relation to the PET surface, while deep learning was used to analyze the images and quantify the extent of degradation. The results showed that F. oxysporum was able to penetrate and degrade the PET surface, forming pits and cracks. The study provides new insights into the mechanisms by which fungi can degrade PET and has implications for the development of biodegradation technologies for plastic waste.

Title: An observational multi-center study on type 2 diabetes treatment prescribing pattern and patient adherence to treatment
Abstract:
**Observational Multi-Center Study on Type 2 Diabetes Treatment Prescribing Pattern and Patient Adherence**

Type 2 diabetes (T2D) is a chronic condition requiring long-term medication adherence for effective management. This observational multi-center study aims to investigate prescribing patterns for T2D medications and assess patient adherence to treatment regimens in real-world clinical settings.

The study will enroll participants with T2D from multiple healthcare centers. Data will be collected from electronic health records, patient interviews, and prescription databases to analyze medication prescribing patterns and adherence rates. The study will also explore factors influencing adherence, such as medication regimen complexity, patient beliefs, and healthcare provider communication.

Findings from this study will provide insights into current treatment practices and patient adherence patterns. The results can inform healthcare providers, patients, and policymakers in optimizing medication regimens and improving outcomes in T2D management.

Title: Exploring the role of electrostatic deposition on inhaled aerosols in alveolated microchannels
Abstract: Electrostatic deposition is a critical process affecting the deposition of inhaled aerosols in alveolated microchannels, impacting respiratory health. As aerosols enter the microchannels, electrostatic forces between the charged particles and the channel walls influence their trajectory and deposition. Understanding these electrostatic interactions is crucial for designing efficient drug delivery systems, preventing particle deposition in undesired lung regions, and assessing potential adverse effects. This research explores the role of electrostatic deposition by investigating the deposition patterns of charged aerosols in realistic alveolated microchannels using computational modeling. The findings provide insights into optimizing aerosol deposition for targeted drug delivery and reducing potential risks associated with inhaled aerosols.

Title: Establishment and validation of nomogram models for overall survival and cancer-specific survival in spindle cell sarcoma patients
Abstract:
Spindle cell sarcoma (SCS) is a rare and aggressive type of cancer characterized by its high mortality rate. Accurate prognostication is essential for guiding treatment decisions and improving patient outcomes. Nomograms are statistical models that combine multiple prognostic factors to predict patient outcomes. This study aimed to establish and validate nomogram models for overall survival (OS) and cancer-specific survival (CSS) in SCS patients.

A retrospective analysis was conducted using data from 183 SCS patients. Univariate and multivariate Cox regression analyses were performed to identify independent prognostic factors.
