Two nomogram models were constructed for OS and CSS, incorporating significant prognostic factors. The models were validated using concordance index (C-index), calibration plots, and decision curve analysis.

The OS nomogram included tumor size, histological subtype, and metastasis status, while the CSS nomogram included tumor size, histological subtype, metastasis status, and surgical margin status. Both nomograms demonstrated good discrimination and calibration. The C-indices for OS and CSS nomograms were 0.70 and 0.72, respectively. Decision curve analysis showed that the nomograms had clinical utility in predicting patient outcomes and guiding treatment decisions.

Title: The association between alcohol, betel nut, and cigarette use with hepatitis C virus infection in Taiwan
Abstract: Hepatitis C virus (HCV) infection is a major public health problem worldwide. Alcohol, betel nut, and cigarette use are common risk factors for HCV infection. In Taiwan, the prevalence of HCV infection is high among people who use these substances. A study conducted in Taiwan found that people who used alcohol, betel nut, and cigarettes were more likely to be infected with HCV than people who did not use these substances. The study also found that the risk of HCV infection was higher among people who used multiple substances. These findings suggest that alcohol, betel nut, and cigarette use are important risk factors for HCV infection in Taiwan.

Title: Detection and classification of brain tumor using hybrid deep learning models
Abstract: Detecting and classifying brain tumors accurately is vital for timely treatment and improved patient outcomes. Hybrid deep learning models are a promising approach in this domain, combining the strengths of traditional machine learning algorithms and deep neural networks. These models leverage the feature extraction capabilities of deep networks and the interpretability of handcrafted features, offering enhanced performance and explainability. By utilizing a hybrid approach, it becomes feasible to handle the inherent complexities and variability commonly encountered in brain tumor analysis. The integration of domain knowledge and the ability to capture intricate relationships among features empower hybrid models to make precise and robust predictions. This approach holds immense potential in advancing clinical decision-making, enabling personalized treatment strategies, and improving overall patient care in the context of brain tumor management.

Title: Sensory innervation of masseter, temporal and lateral pterygoid muscles in common marmosets
Abstract: The common marmoset exhibits precise control of its facial muscles during communication and feeding. Understanding the sensory innervation of the muscles of mastication, including the masseter, temporalis, and lateral pterygoid muscles, is crucial for elucidating the neural mechanisms underlying these behaviors. The sensory innervation of these muscles was investigated using retrograde tracing techniques combined with immunohistochemistry for choline acetyltransferase (ChAT), a marker for motor neurons. The results revealed that the sensory innervation of the masseter and temporalis muscles originates primarily from trigeminal ganglion neurons expressing ChAT. In contrast, the lateral pterygoid muscle receives sensory innervation from both trigeminal and petrosal ganglion neurons expressing ChAT. These findings provide a detailed understanding of the sensory innervation of the key masticatory muscles in common marmosets, contributing to the elucidation of the neural circuitry governing facial muscle control in this species.

Title: Magnetohydrodynamics and viscosity variation in couple stress squeeze film lubrication between rough flat and curved circular plates
Abstract: Magnetohydrodynamics (MHD) and viscosity variation significantly influence the behavior of squeeze film lubrication between rough flat and curved circular plates. MHD introduces Lorentz forces that modify the pressure distribution and load-carrying capacity, while viscosity variation due to shear thinning or thickening effects alters the film thickness and friction characteristics. The interaction between these phenomena leads to a complex lubrication regime that requires advanced mathematical modeling and numerical simulation for analysis. Understanding the interplay of MHD and viscosity variation is crucial for optimizing lubrication performance in devices such as magnetic bearings, microelectromechanical systems (MEMS), and biomedical applications.

Title: A prospective cohort study of periostin as a serum biomarker in patients with idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis treated with nintedanib
Abstract: A prospective cohort study was conducted to evaluate the role of periostin as a serum biomarker in patients with idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF) treated with nintedanib. Serum periostin levels were measured at baseline and at follow-up visits in patients with IPF who were treated with nintedanib. The primary outcome was the change in serum periostin levels from baseline to follow-up. The results showed that serum periostin levels decreased significantly from baseline to follow-up in patients with IPF who were treated with nintedanib. This decrease was associated with an improvement in lung function and a reduction in the risk of disease progression. These findings suggest that serum periostin may be a useful biomarker for monitoring disease activity and response to treatment in patients with IPF.

Title: Automated tracking of cell migration in phase contrast images with CellTraxx
Abstract:
CellTraxx is a user-friendly Fiji plugin for automated, high-throughput tracking of cell migration in phase contrast microscopy images. It combines deep learning-based segmentation with machine learning-powered tracking algorithms to accurately track individual cells over time. CellTraxx offers various features:

1. **Accurate Segmentation**: It uses a deep learning model trained on a diverse dataset to segment cells with high accuracy, even in dense or overlapping regions.

2. **Robust Tracking**: The tracking algorithm employs machine learning techniques to handle cell division, merging, and disappearance events effectively.

3. **Speed and Scalability**: CellTraxx is optimized for speed and can handle large datasets efficiently, making it suitable for high-throughput screening applications.

4. **User-Friendly Interface**: The plugin provides a user-friendly graphical interface that allows researchers to easily set tracking parameters and visualize results.

5. **Extensibility**: CellTraxx offers a Python API for customization and integration with other image analysis pipelines.

By leveraging these features, CellTraxx enables researchers to automate the complex task of cell migration tracking, reducing manual labor and analysis time, and providing reliable and quantitative data for studying cell motility and behavior.

Title: Dual barrier system against xenomitochondrial contamination in mouse embryos
Abstract: Xenomitochondrial contamination occurs when mitochondria from a donor cell are accidentally transferred into a recipient cell during assisted reproductive technologies (ART). To prevent this, a dual barrier system has been developed for mouse embryos. This system involves using two different types of mitochondrial inhibitors: one that blocks mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) replication and another that inhibits mtDNA transcription. By using two inhibitors, the system is more effective at preventing xenomitochondrial contamination than using either inhibitor alone. The dual barrier system has been shown to be safe and effective in preventing xenomitochondrial contamination in mouse embryos, and it is now being considered for use in human ART.

Title: Ubiquinol attenuates -radiation induced coronary and aortic changes via PDGF/p38 MAPK/ICAM-1 related pathway
Abstract: Ubiquinol, a reduced form of coenzyme Q10, protects against various cardiovascular diseases. However, its effect on -radiation-induced coronary and aortic changes remains unclear. This study investigated the protective effects of ubiquinol on -radiation-induced coronary and aortic changes and explored the underlying mechanisms. Rats were exposed to -radiation (5 Gy) and treated with ubiquinol (50 mg/kg/day). Radiation exposure significantly increased coronary and aortic wall thickness, intima-media thickness, and lipid deposition. Ubiquinol treatment attenuated these changes and suppressed -radiation-induced upregulation of platelet-derived growth factor (PDGF), p38 mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK), and intercellular adhesion molecule-1 (ICAM-1). Inhibition of PDGF, p38 MAPK, or ICAM-1 abrogated the protective effects of ubiquinol. These findings suggest that ubiquinol attenuates -radiation-induced coronary and aortic changes by inhibiting the PDGF/p38 MAPK/ICAM-1 pathway, providing a potential therapeutic strategy for radiation-induced cardiovascular complications.

Title: Obesity-induced PARIS (ZNF746) accumulation in adipose progenitor cells leads to attenuated mitochondrial biogenesis and impaired adipogenesis
Abstract: Obesity-induced PARIS (ZNF746) accumulation in adipose progenitor cells leads to attenuated mitochondrial biogenesis and impaired adipogenesis. PARIS, a pro-apoptotic zinc finger protein, is highly expressed in obesity and associated with insulin resistance. In adipose progenitor cells (APCs), PARIS accumulation impairs mitochondrial biogenesis and adipogenesis. PARIS overexpression reduces mitochondrial DNA copy number, oxygen consumption, and ATP production. It also inhibits the expression of genes involved in mitochondrial biogenesis, such as PGC-1 and NRF-1. Furthermore, PARIS overexpression impairs adipogenesis by inhibiting the expression of adipogenic transcription factors, such as PPAR and C/EBP. These findings suggest that PARIS accumulation in APCs contributes to obesity-induced mitochondrial dysfunction and impaired adipogenesis, which may lead to insulin resistance and metabolic dysfunction.

Title: A rapid and reference-free imputation method for low-cost genotyping platforms
Abstract:
Low-cost genotyping platforms such as the Axiom Genotyping Array have revolutionized the field of genomics by enabling large-scale genetic studies at reduced costs. However, these platforms often suffer from missing genotypes due to various factors, which can lead to reduced statistical power and biased results. Reference-based imputation methods are commonly used to address missing genotypes, but they rely on external reference panels, which may not always be available or appropriate. 
Here we introduce a rapid and reference-free imputation method, FastPhase, specifically designed for low-cost genotyping platforms. FastPhase leverages local haplotype information to impute missing genotypes without relying on external reference data. It uses a novel algorithm to iteratively update haplotype probabilities based on observed genotypes, resulting in accurate imputation of missing genotypes even in regions with complex haplotype structures. FastPhase is computationally efficient, making it suitable for imputing large datasets. 
In summary, FastPhase provides a rapid and reference-free solution for imputing missing genotypes in low-cost genotyping platforms, enabling more accurate and comprehensive analysis of genetic data.

Title: Real-time multi-contrast magnetic particle imaging for the detection of gastrointestinal bleeding
Abstract:
Real-time multi-contrast magnetic particle imaging (MPI) is a novel imaging technique that allows for the detection and localization of gastrointestinal (GI) bleeding in real time. MPI utilizes superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoparticles (SPIONs) that are injected intravenously and accumulate at the site of bleeding. These SPIONs generate a magnetic field that can be detected by an MPI scanner, creating an image of the bleeding site.

The use of multiple contrasts in MPI enhances the sensitivity and specificity of the technique. For example, different SPIONs can be labeled with different fluorescent dyes, allowing for the detection of both active and inactive bleeding sites. Additionally, the use of different magnetic field strengths can provide information about the depth and size of the bleeding site.

Real-time MPI has the potential to revolutionize the diagnosis and management of GI bleeding. By providing real-time visualization of the bleeding site, MPI can guide endoscopic interventions and reduce the need for exploratory surgery. Furthermore, MPI can be used to monitor the efficacy of treatment and assess the risk of rebleeding.

Title: Whole-genome sequencing provides novel insights into the evolutionary history and genetic adaptation of reindeer populations in northern Eurasia
Abstract: Whole-genome sequencing has unlocked unprecedented insights into the evolutionary history and genetic adaptation of reindeer populations in northern Eurasia. Comparative analyses have revealed distinct genetic lineages reflecting past isolation and adaptation to diverse Arctic environments. Studies have identified key genes involved in cold tolerance, dietary preferences, and immune responses. Evidence suggests that reindeer populations have experienced multiple episodes of gene flow and hybridization, shaping their genetic diversity and adaptive potential. Genomic data also provides valuable information for conservation and management strategies, enabling the identification of unique populations and assessing genetic diversity within and between reindeer herds.

Title: Genome analysis of triple phages that curtails MDRE. coliwith ML based host receptor prediction and its evaluation
Abstract:
Genome analysis of triple phages that curtails MDR E. coli with ML-based host receptor prediction and its evaluation:

The emergence of multidrug-resistant (MDR) bacteria poses a serious threat to global health. Escherichia coli is a common MDR pathogen that causes various infections, including urinary tract infections, sepsis, and pneumonia. Phage therapy, using viruses that specifically infect and kill bacteria, has emerged as a promising alternative to antibiotics for treating MDR infections. However, the effectiveness of phage therapy can be limited by the ability of bacteria to develop resistance to phages. To address this challenge, we conducted a genome analysis of three phages infecting MDR E. coli and developed an ML-based method to predict host receptors. Our findings provide valuable insights into the molecular mechanisms underlying phage-host interactions and offer a novel approach to guide phage selection and enhance the efficacy of phage therapy against MDR E. coli.

Title: Microfluidic devices for precise measurements of cell directionality reveal a role for glutamine during cell migration
Abstract: Microfluidic devices provide a powerful platform for precisely measuring cell directionality and studying the underlying mechanisms. Here, we describe the development of a microfluidic device that enables real-time monitoring of cell migration in a controlled environment. Using this device, we demonstrate that the amino acid glutamine promotes cell directionality and migration speed by regulating the activity of the small GTPase Rac1 and the actin cytoskeleton. Our findings reveal a novel role for glutamine in cell migration and highlight the potential of microfluidic devices for dissecting complex cellular processes with high precision and control.

Title: Impact of various high fat diets on gene expression and the microbiome across the mouse intestines
Abstract:
High-fat diets have significant impacts on gene expression and the microbiome in the mouse intestines. Studies have shown that consuming a high-fat diet leads to alterations in the expression of genes involved in lipid metabolism, inflammation, and immune response. These changes can contribute to the development of metabolic disorders such as obesity and type 2 diabetes.

In addition to gene expression, high-fat diets also affect the composition and diversity of the gut microbiome. The microbiome is a complex community of microorganisms that reside in the intestines and play crucial roles in various physiological processes. A high-fat diet can disrupt the balance of the microbiome, leading to an increase in harmful bacteria and a decrease in beneficial bacteria. This imbalance can contribute to intestinal inflammation and impaired immune function.

Understanding the impact of high-fat diets on gene expression and the microbiome is essential for developing strategies to prevent and treat metabolic disorders. By manipulating the diet or using probiotics, it may be possible to mitigate the negative effects of high-fat diets and promote a healthier gut environment.

Title: Transformer fault diagnosis method based on TLR-ADASYN balanced dataset
Abstract: The transformer is one of the most important equipment in the power system. Therefore, fault diagnosis of the transformer is of great significance to ensure the safe operation of the power system. However, there are many challenges in fault diagnosis of the transformer, such as the complexity of the transformer structure, the randomness of the fault conditions, and the imbalance of the fault dataset. To address these challenges, we propose a novel transformer fault diagnosis method based on TLR-ADASYN balanced dataset. The proposed method first uses transfer learning (TL) to transfer the knowledge learned from a source domain (e.g., healthy transformer) to a target domain (e.g., faulty transformer). Then, the synthetic minority over-sampling technique (ADASYN) is used to balance the fault dataset, which can improve the classification performance of the fault diagnosis model. Finally, we use a deep neural network (DNN) to classify the fault types. The proposed method is validated on a real transformer fault dataset, and the experimental results show that the proposed method outperforms the existing methods in terms of classification accuracy and robustness.

Title: Study on the microcrystal cellulose and the derived 2D graphene and relative carbon materials
Abstract:
Microcrystal cellulose (MCC) is a versatile biomaterial with a unique combination of properties, including high crystallinity, high aspect ratio, and low density. It has been widely used in various applications, such as papermaking, food additives, and drug delivery. In recent years, there has been growing interest in using MCC as a precursor for the synthesis of 2D graphene and other carbon materials.

The conversion of MCC to graphene can be achieved through a variety of methods, such as hydrothermal treatment, chemical exfoliation, and thermal annealing. The resulting graphene materials exhibit excellent electrical, thermal, and mechanical properties, making them promising candidates for applications in electronics, energy storage, and composites.

In addition to graphene, MCC can also be used to synthesize other carbon materials, such as carbon nanotubes, carbon nanofibers, and carbon spheres. These materials have unique properties and potential applications in various fields, such as catalysis, energy storage, and environmental remediation.

The study of MCC and the derived 2D graphene and carbon materials is a rapidly growing field. With the development of new synthesis methods and the exploration of new applications, these materials are expected to play an increasingly important role in various industries.

Title: Microbial processes with the potential to mobilize As from a circumneutral-pH mixture of flotation and roaster tailings
Abstract: Microbial processes offer promising avenues for mobilizing arsenic (As) from flotation and roaster tailings, commonly generated during mining operations and posing environmental concerns due to As contamination. Acidithiobacillus thiooxidans and Leptospirillum ferriphilum, acidophilic bacteria, can oxidize iron sulfides in tailings, releasing As into solution. Other bacteria, such as Shewanella putrefaciens and Geobacter metallireducens, can reduce iron(III) oxides and hydroxides, further mobilizing As. Fungi like Penicillium chrysogenum and Aspergillus niger can produce organic acids and chelating agents, enhancing As solubilization. Bioleaching and biosorption techniques utilizing these microorganisms can effectively extract As from tailings, facilitating its recovery and reducing environmental risks.

Title: The impact mechanism of ownership change on university innovation
Abstract:
**The Impact Mechanism of Ownership Change on University Innovation**

Ownership change in universities, such as through mergers or acquisitions, can have significant implications for innovation.

**Positive Impacts:**

* **Increased resources and capabilities:** Acquisition by larger or more resource-rich institutions can provide universities with improved research funding, infrastructure, and expertise, facilitating innovation.
* **Diversity of perspectives:** Ownership changes can bring together different research strengths and perspectives, fostering cross-disciplinary collaboration and generating innovative ideas.
* **Access to external networks:** Acquired universities may gain access to broader networks of industry, government, and other research institutions, providing opportunities for collaboration and innovation.

**Negative Impacts:**

* **Culture clashes and resistance:** Ownership changes can disrupt existing university cultures and norms, potentially hindering innovation if not managed effectively.
* **Loss of autonomy and control:** Acquired universities may have less autonomy in decision-making and research priorities, which can limit their ability to pursue innovative projects.
* **Duplication and overlap:** Merging universities with similar research strengths can lead to duplication of efforts and reduced efficiency, potentially stifling innovation.

Title: Spatial and temporal evolution and influencing factors of tourism eco-efficiency in Fujian province under the target of carbon peak
Abstract: Under the target of carbon peaking, Fujian Province vigorously develops tourism eco-efficiency. In this study, the spatial-temporal evolution of tourism eco-efficiency was measured by the super-efficiency slacks-based measure (Super-SBM) model, and the influencing factors were analyzed by the geographically weighted regression (GWR) model. The results showed that: (1) The overall tourism eco-efficiency of Fujian Province showed a fluctuating upward trend from 2010 to 2019, with an average annual growth rate of 2.85%. (2) The spatial distribution of tourism eco-efficiency is unbalanced, with high values in the southeast coastal areas and low values in the northwest inland areas. (3) The influencing factors of tourism eco-efficiency vary in different regions. In most areas, government regulation, scientific and technological innovation, and transportation infrastructure have positive effects on tourism eco-efficiency, while energy consumption and population density have negative effects.

Title: A comparative study of ultrasound cycloplasty and endoscopic cyclophotocoagulation in the treatment of secondary glaucoma
Abstract:
Ultrasound cycloplasty (USC) and endoscopic cyclophotocoagulation (ECP) are minimally invasive glaucoma surgeries used to reduce intraocular pressure (IOP) in secondary glaucoma, where the angle between the cornea and iris is blocked.

USC uses high-frequency ultrasound to create small, targeted lesions in the ciliary body, reducing aqueous humor production. ECP uses a laser fiber inserted into the eye through a small incision to deliver controlled thermal energy to the ciliary body, also reducing aqueous humor production.

Both USC and ECP have comparable efficacy in lowering IOP and improving visual function in secondary glaucoma. However, USC may have a longer duration of effect, while ECP has a lower risk of postoperative inflammation. The choice of procedure depends on factors such as the underlying cause of glaucoma, the patient's anatomy, and the surgeon's experience.

Title: Convergent differentiation of multiciliated cells
Abstract: Convergent differentiation of multiciliated cells refers to the formation of a specific type of ciliated cell, called a multiciliated cell, through different developmental pathways in various species and tissues. Multiciliated cells are characterized by the presence of multiple cilia on their apical surface and are involved in specialized functions such as mucus clearance and fluid flow. The convergent differentiation of multiciliated cells arises from distinct genetic and molecular mechanisms, despite their functional similarities. Comparative studies between different organisms have uncovered conserved regulatory pathways and transcription factors involved in promoting multiciliogenesis, while species-specific adaptations and variations in gene expression profiles contribute to the diversity observed in multiciliated cell formation.

Title: Cannabis Sativatargets mediobasal hypothalamic neurons to stimulate appetite
Abstract:
Cannabis Sativa, the plant from which marijuana is derived, has been found to stimulate appetite by targeting mediobasal hypothalamic (MBH) neurons. The MBH is a brain region involved in regulating hunger and metabolism. When activated, MBH neurons release hormones that signal the body to eat.

Cannabinoids, the active compounds in Cannabis Sativa, bind to receptors on MBH neurons and activate them. This activation leads to the release of orexigenic hormones, such as neuropeptide Y (NPY) and agouti-related peptide (AgRP), which stimulate appetite.

The ability of Cannabis Sativa to stimulate appetite has led to its use as a treatment for conditions that cause weight loss, such as cancer and AIDS. However, more research is needed to determine the long-term effects of Cannabis Sativa use on appetite and weight.

Title: Statistical analysis of synonymous and stop codons in pseudo-random and real sequences as a function of GC content
Abstract: Statistical analysis of synonymous and stop codons in pseudo-random and real sequences as a function of GC content explores the distribution of these codons in different contexts. Synonymous codons are those that code for the same amino acid, while stop codons signal the end of protein translation. By comparing the frequencies of these codons in random sequences and real biological sequences, researchers can gain insights into the evolutionary forces shaping codon usage. GC content, the proportion of guanine and cytosine nucleotides in a sequence, is known to influence codon usage patterns. This analysis investigates how GC content affects the distribution of synonymous and stop codons, providing valuable information for understanding the evolution of genetic sequences and the underlying mechanisms of gene expression.

Title: Greedy routing optimisation in hyperbolic networks
Abstract: In hyperbolic networks with negative curvature, greedy routing has been shown to perform well in many cases. However, in some cases, greedy routing can lead to sub-optimal paths. In order to address this issue, researchers have developed a number of optimisation techniques for greedy routing in hyperbolic networks. These techniques aim to find paths that are close to the optimal paths, while still maintaining the simplicity and efficiency of greedy routing. One common approach is to use a local search algorithm to iteratively improve the path found by greedy routing. Another approach is to use a more sophisticated routing algorithm that takes into account the curvature of the network. These optimisation techniques can significantly improve the performance of greedy routing in hyperbolic networks, while still maintaining its simplicity and efficiency.

Title: Solving the mystery of the FMC63-CD19 affinity
Abstract: The affinity between FMC63 and CD19 is crucial for the development of chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T-cell therapies. However, the molecular basis of this interaction remains elusive. Recent studies have employed advanced techniques such as X-ray crystallography, cryo-electron microscopy, and computational modeling to unravel the structural details of the FMC63-CD19 complex. These investigations have revealed key amino acid residues and conformational changes that contribute to the high affinity and specificity of this interaction. Understanding the molecular mechanisms underlying FMC63-CD19 affinity is essential for optimizing CAR T-cell therapies, improving their efficacy, and reducing potential adverse effects.

Title: PORTLAND INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE ON MANAGEMENT OF ENGINEERING AND TECHNOLOGY
Abstract: The Portland International Conference on Management of Engineering and Technology (PICMET) is a global forum for academics, researchers, industry professionals, and policymakers to share cutting-edge research, exchange innovative ideas, and explore best practices in management of engineering and technology. PICMET covers a wide range of topics, including technology management, engineering management, innovation management, project management, and sustainable development. The conference attracts attendees from around the world and provides opportunities for networking, collaboration, and professional development. PICMET is organized by the Portland International Center for Management of Engineering and Technology (PICMET), a non-profit organization dedicated to advancing knowledge and practice in the field.
